`test_write_to_dlq` writes to a hard-coded relative path (`nats_dlq.txt`). Since Rust tests run in parallel by default, this can be flaky if other tests (or another run) touches the same file, and it can also leave artifacts when the test fails mid-run. Consider writing to a unique temp file/directory (e.g., via `tempfile`) or setting `NATS_DLQ_PATH` to a per-test path.
```suggestion
    use std::env;
    use tempfile::NamedTempFile;
    #[tokio::test]
    async fn test_write_to_dlq() {
        let subject = "test.dlq.subject";
        let payload = r#"{"test":"dlq_payload"}"#;

        // Use a unique temporary file for this test's DLQ path to avoid interference.
        let temp_file = NamedTempFile::new().unwrap();
        let dlq_path = temp_file.path().to_string_lossy().to_string();
        env::set_var("NATS_DLQ_PATH", &dlq_path);

        let result = NatsPublisherWorker::write_to_dlq(subject, payload).await;
        assert!(result.is_ok());

        let contents = tokio::fs::read_to_string(&dlq_path).await.unwrap();
        assert!(contents.contains(&format!("[{}] {}\n", subject, payload)));
```
